  "prompt": "Which food should I not eat after getting a tattoo?",
  "response": "After getting a tattoo, it's important to be mindful of your diet to support the healing process and minimize potential complications. Here are some foods you should avoid or limit:\n\n### 1. **Highly Processed Foods**  \n   - **Why:** Foods high in sugar, artificial additives, and unhealthy fats can promote inflammation and slow down the healing process.\n\n### 2. **Excessive Sugar**  \n   - **Why:** Cons too much sugar can impair your immune system and increase inflammation, which may delay tattoo healing.\n\n### 3. **High-Sodium Foods**  \n   - **Why:** Too much salt can cause dehydration and swelling, which can affect the appearance of your fresh tattoo.\n\n### 4. **Spicy Foods**  \n   - **Why:** Spicy foods can cause sweating, which may irritate the tattooed area and increase the risk of infection.\n\n### 5. **Alcohol**  \n   - **Why:** Alcohol can thin your blood, increase swelling, and impair your body\u2019s natural healing process.\n\n### 6. **Caffeine**  \n   - **Why:** Excessive caffeine can dehydrate your skin, making it harder for the tattoo to heal properly.\n\n### 7. **Seafood**  \n   - **Why:** For some people, seafood (especially shellfish) can trigger allergic reactions or cause inflammation, which may interfere with healing.\n\n### 8. **Raw or Undercooked Foods**  \n   - **Why:** These foods pose a higher risk of bacterial contamination, which could lead to infections that compromise your tattoo\u2019s healing.\n\n### What to Eat Instead:  \nTo promote healing, focus on nutrient-rich foods like:  \n- **Fruits and Vegetables:** Packed with vitamins and antioxidants.  \n- **Lean Proteins:** Helps repair skin tissue.  \n- **Healthy Fats:** Like those found in nuts, seeds, and avocados.  \n- **Hydrating Foods:** Such as watermelon, cucumbers, and leafy greens.\n\nBy avoiding the listed foods and focusing on a balanced, healing-friendly diet, you\u2019ll give your tattoo the best chance to heal beautifully. Also, stay hydrated and follow your tattoo artist\u2019s aftercare instructions!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
